<p><b>Should I learn Japanese or kanji first?</b> Should I learn Kanji first before I study? You should study Kanji progressively. If you don't know much Japanese, learning Kanji will not benefit you as much as it will once you have built up more vocabulary and grammar. YesJapan teaches 5 to 10 Kanji at the end of each lesson, starting with Course 3.</p>
